data.content:
Yes! Two better options depending on your needs:

**1. `[DataRow]`** — best when all values are compile-time constants (your case):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Tuple-based `DynamicData`** (MSTest 3.4+) — for when you need computed/non-constant data but still want type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

The tuple approach replaces `IEnumerable<object[]>` with `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`, so the compiler catches type mismatches at build time rather than at test runtime. For your example, `[DataRow]` is the simplest choice.
